\f0\i0\fs28 \cf0 Although you can run standard UNIX programs and commands on a NEXTSPACE computer, such programs aren\'92t designed to be run directly from the workspace.  Traditional UNIX constructs such as standard input and standard output, which many UNIX-style programs depend on, aren\'92t part of the workspace interface.\
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\fs16 \cf0 \
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 To run these programs, you can use the Terminal application.  Terminal offers a number of useful features:\
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\fs16 \cf0 \
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2480\fi-380\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 \'b7	Scrollers let you scroll backward to text that has already disappeared from the window.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 \'b7	Text can be copied and pasted within a Terminal window, between windows, or to and from other applications that support cutting and pasting, such as Mail and Edit.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 \'b7	Terminal has a Print command to let you print the contents of a window, and a Find command to let you search for text.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 \'b7	Terminal\'92s Services menu lets you make interapplication requests, such as defining a word in Digital Webster
\f1\fs18 \'99
\f0\fs28 or searching for references in the Digital Librarian
\f1\fs18 \'99
\f0\fs28 .  You can also define your own Terminal services for use in other appications.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 \'b7	Terminal\'92s Preferences command allows you to change the size, title bar text, emulation characteristics, and font properties of one or more Terminal windows.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 \'b7	Terminal provides strict VT100
\f1\fs18 \'99
\f0\fs28  terminal emulation.  Every UNIX program or utility you run (such as Emacs or 
\f4\b vi
\f0\b0 ) should work as intended.\

\fs16 \
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

