\cf0 When \'93Alternate key generates Escape sequences\'94 is selected, typing a character while you hold down the Alternate key causes a two-character sequence to be generated\'d0an Escape character followed by the character you typed.  (This is useful when running Emacs, so you can use the Alternate key as a Meta key).  Click \'93Alternate key generates special characters\'94 if you want Alternate key combinations to generate a single character with the high bit set.  Some programs interpret special characters in their own way, so this doesn\'92t always work as expected; Emacs, for example, simply strips out the high bit from special characters.\
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\fs16 \cf0 \
\pard\li2100\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 Note:  
\f0\b0 If necessary, you can specify a character other than Escape as the first character in a two-character sequence.  To do so, use the 
\f4\b dwrite
\f0\b0  shell command to set the value of the Terminal 
\f4\b Meta
\f0\b0  variable to the decimal value of the desired character.\

