\cf0 The Find panel locates the next occurrence of a specified string, and can search either forwards or backwards.  In the Find field, enter the string to search for.  The controls in the Find panel have these effects:\
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\fs16 \cf0 \
\pard\tx6140\tx10180\li2480\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 \

\fs28 Control	Effect\
\pard\tx6140\tx10420\li6140\fi-3660\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 Next	Selects the first occurrence of the Find string following the current selection or insertion point.  (Pressing the Return key has the same effect, but with one difference:  If you\'92ve used the keyboard alternative to display the panel, pressing Return causes the panel to disappear instead of remaining on the screen.)\

\fs16 \

\fs28 Previous	Selects the first occurrence of the Find string, searching backward from the current selection or insertion point.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 Ignore Case	Makes the find operation case-insensitive (that is, capitalization is ignored when determining a match).  If this box is unchecked, the search is case-sensitive.\

\fs16 \
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 If the end of the text is reached, Find continues searching from the beginning (conversely, when searching backward, if the beginning of the text is reached, Find continues searching from the end).\
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\fs16 \cf0 \
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 If no instance of the Find string is located, Terminal beeps and the message \'93Not Found\'94 appears in the Find panel.\
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\fs16 \cf0 \
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 Commands in the Find menu (which is in the Edit menu) provide alternatives and shortcuts to using the Find panel.  There\'92s also a Jump to Selection command for scrolling the insertion point into view.  For more information, see \'93Terminal Command Reference\'94 at the end of this chapter.\
