\fs48 Commands in the Shell Menu\

\fs16 \
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs28 \cf0 Terminal\'92s Shell menu provides the following commands.\
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\fs16 \cf0 \
\pard\tx6140\tx10180\li2480\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 \

\fs28 Command	Description\
\pard\tx6140\tx10420\li6140\fi-3660\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 Open	Opens an existing shell window or set of shell windows that have previously been saved in a file using the Save (or Save As) command.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 New	Opens a new shell window, using the default settings.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 Run Command	Displays a panel in which you enter a UNIX command to be run.  The command is run in a new Terminal window.   (The command is displayed as the title of the window; when the process running in the window has completed, the title changes to \'93Dead Terminal.\'94)\

\fs16 \

\fs28 Save, Save As	Saves a window or set of windows to a file, allowing you to save and reuse your preferred configurations.  See \'93Saving a Terminal Configuration for Later Use.\'94\

\fs16 \

\fs28 Set Title	Displays a panel for you to edit and set the current title of the window.  The Preferences panel allows greater control over this \'96 you can combine your own text with Terminal\'92s automatically updated information.  See \'93Title Bar Preferences\'93 for more information.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 Steal Keys	Allows you to effectively debug an application from a shell window in which the GNU debugger is running.  The debugging process frequently involves alternately activating Terminal (to type debugger commands) and the other application (to test the application being debugged).  However, clicking to alternatively activate and deactivate the application being debugged causes the application to change its state in unpredictable ways.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 	To let you get around this problem, the Steal Keys command puts Terminal in a special debugging mode.  In this mode, Terminal can be activated or deactivated simply by moving the cursor into or out of the Terminal shell window.  Therefore, you can easily activate Terminal whenever you want to type a debugger command, without clicking and thus affecting the state of the application you\'92re debugging.  \

\fs16 \

\fs28 	When you\'92re ready to exit debugging mode, click in the Terminal window to make the Terminal main menu reappear, and then choose this command again (its name will have changed to Yield Keys).\

\fs16 \

\fs28 Page Layout	Displays the standard Page Layout panel, which lets you choose among various paper sizes, scaling factors, and orientations for text printed from the main window.\

\fs16 \
\pard\tx6140\tx10420\li2100\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 \
\
