\fs48 Commands in the Edit Menu\

\fs16 \
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs28 \cf0 Terminal\'92s Edit menu provides the standard editing and text-searching commands, which can be used for finding and editing text in a Terminal window.\
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\fs16 \cf0 \
\pard\tx6140\tx10180\li2480\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 Command	Description\
\pard\tx6140\tx10420\li6140\fi-3660\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 Cut, Copy,  Paste	These commands let you copy or move text, either between Terminal windows or between a Terminal window and another window that supports copying and pasting.  To duplicate text, select the text and choose Copy.  To insert the most recently cut or copied text at the Terminal window\'92s command-line cursor location, choose Paste.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 	Copy puts a copy of the selected text onto the pasteboard, from where it can be pasted with the Paste command.  The pasteboard holds just one selection; each Copy operation overwrites the previous contents of the pasteboard.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 	
\f4\b Note:
\f0\b0   Cut is always disabled.  The only way to remove text from a Terminal window is to use the Clear Buffer command.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 Find	Displays a menu that contains commands for finding text, as described below in \'93Commands in the Find Menu.\'94\

\fs16 \

\fs28 Clear Buffer	Removes text from the scrollback buffer, leaving just the current command line.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 Select All	Selects all the text in the main window.  This is useful, for example, when you want to copy the entire range of text to another application, such as Edit.\

\fs16 \
\pard\tx6140\tx10420\li2100\partightenfactor0

