\fs48 Commands in the Find Menu \

\fs16 \
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs28 \cf0 The Find menu contains commands that let you search for text in the main Terminal window.\
\pard\tx2480\tx2860\tx3240\li2100\partightenfactor0

\fs16 \cf0 \
\pard\tx6140\tx10180\li2480\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs28 \cf0 Command	Description\
\pard\tx6140\tx10420\li6140\fi-3660\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0 \cf0 Find Panel	Opens the Find panel, which allows you to locate the next occurrence of a specified string.  For more information, see \'93Finding Text in a Terminal Window.\'94\

\fs16 \

\fs28 Find Next, Find Previous	These are the standard Find menu commands.  The Find Next command performs the same function as the Next button in the Find panel, and Find Previous is the same as the Find panel\'92s Previous button.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 Enter Selection	Copies the selected text in the main window into the Find panel\'92s Find field, even if the Find panel isn\'92t open or the key window.\

\fs16 \

\fs28 Jump to Selection	When the insertion point or current text selection isn\'92t showing in the main window, the Jump to Selection command scrolls it into view.  If there\'92s no insertion point or current text selection, this command scrolls to the end of the buffer.  \

\fs16 \

\fs28 	
\f4\b Note:
\f0\b0   Clicking in a Terminal window positions the insertion point where you clicked.  However, the insertion point isn\'92t visible since it\'92s not possible to perform any copy or paste operation on it.  This may cause some confusion, since the Jump to Selection command may sometimes jump to a location that doesn\'92t appear to have any selected text associated with it.\

\fs16 \
\pard\tx6140\tx10420\li2100\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 \
\
\
